I like the idea, but your calculations are all wrong. An object in the orbit described would take about 90 minutes to circle the Earth, not 8/9 of a day. The tidal effect wouldn't be anywhere near as strong as you describe if the object was made of ordinary rock, but you could fix that by explaining that it seems to be made of some super-high-density substance.

The height of the tides induced on Earth will be proportional to the mass of the inducing body divided by the cube of its distance (from the centre of the Earth, not the surface). If the object induces tides about as strong as the Sun, which is about half as strong as the Moon (which is about as weak as it could be and still have anything like the described effects), its mass is 1.8e17g/cm3.







